Subject:    limiting data access by name servers
From:       <a href="?a=95837785800025&r=1&w=2">pma%hpcndm () hplabs ! HP ! COM</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198812">1988-12-08 13:17:06</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837783027035&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837783027035&q=raw">body</a>]</b>


With the advent of the TXT data type, general information can be stored
in name servers.  Some of the information my be intended for the general
public and some for "internal use only".

Have there been discussions in the past for limiting access to the data
contained in name servers?  If so, what were the issues?

These are the limitations that I view as useful:

	1) what hosts a name server will answer queries for
	2) what hosts a name server will allow zone transfers
	3) what hosts a name server will handle recursive queries for

Since DNS packets do not contain enough information to handle this on 
a per user basis, simple security can be handled on a per host or per
network basis.  Thus, we could limit access to some or all of the data
to the local host, the LAN, or specific networks.

Has anyone considered tagging individual data or whole domains with
access lists of IP addresses or network numbers?  These tags would need
to be passed along with zone transfers.

Paul Albitz
pma%hpcndm@hplabs.hp.com

